      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Etadanik Mistmorgue</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Duels are stupid one way or the other because it doesn't reflect how either class really fights.  Does the necro fight by augmenting his pet and then letting him tank without doing anything? Does the mage fight without a damage shield and nukes or chain-casting? All a parse shows is the default mob-strength of the two pets, in which case the EoT proved to be very close to the GV.  Is that fair? Well heck I don't know - is the unbuffed Beastlord pet with no procs worth a penny? Is it fair that the pets are dueled in a fashion in which they aren't used? I mean, let's be frank here - who here thinks chain-casting the EoT is a valid necro exp tactic, and who feels that tanking for the GVs is one?</P><P>Should mages have the best pets? Sure, that's always been a little feature of the mage class and should be kept where it's at.  The question really is what defines having the best pet? Is it having the most powerful pet under the best circumstances? In which case one can argue that mages have the most powerful *summoned* pet (the Epic) but that enchanters have the most powerful pet under specific circumstances because of Dire Charm and Dictate.  Is it having the most powerful pet at all times, every level? In which case it could be argued that the necro and mage come very close at level 59 in terms of pure pet strength.  Is it having the most efficient and "best bang for the buck" pets? In which case mages win hands down.  Is it having the best pet buffs? In which case beast lords might march in and dwarf us all.  Or is it all of these things, combined together?</P><P>The measures of power are many indeed; who can say which one to heed?</P><P><BR>Etadanik the Redeemed</font></td>
